<h2 data-pm-slice="1 1 []"><span data-color="var(--green-10)">What Crypto Exchange Fees Do Platforms Charge?</span></h2>
<h3><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Maker And Taker Fees When You Buy Sell Crypto</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Maker and taker fees are the way most crypto exchanges charge traders for using their services. These fees depend on how you trade—specifically, whether your trade adds liquidity to the market or takes it away.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A maker is someone who places a limit order that doesn’t get executed right away. This order can be for buying or selling cryptocurrency at a price that isn’t currently available. By setting a trade at a price that’s not yet established, the maker adds liquidity to the market, acting as either a buyer or seller while they wait for their order to go through. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Example</span><b>:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> You place a limit order to buy Bitcoin at $65,000 when the current price is $65,200. Your order waits in the book until the price drops; it makes liquidity available to others. Exchanges often reward makers with lower fees (or even rebates) because they improve market depth and stability.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">On the other hand, a taker is someone who opts for a market order that gets executed immediately. A taker can also place a limit order that matches an existing one, which results in an instant execution as well. When a taker makes a transaction, they pull liquidity from the market because their trade happens right away.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Example: You buy Bitcoin instantly at the current market price. Your order takes</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">liquidity since it matches an existing sell order. Taker fees are typically higher than maker fees because takers consume liquidity.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Keep in mind that both makers and takers are involved in the market as participants or investors, but they aren&#8217;t the ones creating the cryptocurrency itself.</span></p>
<h3 data-pm-slice="1 1 []"><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Fiat-to-Crypto Fees and Blockchain Gas Fees</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fiat-to-crypto and crypto-to-crypto fees are the costs associated with swapping national currencies (fiat) for digital assets or trading one cryptocurrency for another. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When it comes to fiat-to-crypto fees, you usually have to consider both the platform&#8217;s charges and any network or bank fees that come into play during deposits and withdrawals. Under fiat-to-crypto fees, we have:</span></p>
<p><b>On-ramp/Off-ramp Fees</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: You’ll pay a fee to bring money in (on-ramp) or take it back out (off-ramp) of the crypto ecosystem.</span></p>
<p><b>Platform Fees</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: There may be a fee for the conversion itself, often a percentage of the transaction, at exchanges or crypto payment services.</span></p>
<p><b>Banking Fees</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: Conventional banks and payment processors (such as Visa or Mastercard) can also impose fees for using their services.</span></p>
<p><b>Network Fees</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: For fiat-to-crypto transactions there typically aren’t any fees related to the network on the blockchain (since it’s on traditional payment rails).</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">On the other hand, crypto-to-crypto fees generally include the exchange&#8217;s trading fees, whether you&#8217;re a maker or a taker, along with any potential network fees for moving assets across the blockchain.</span></p>
<h3 data-pm-slice="1 1 []"><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Deposit and Withdrawal Fees: What to Expect</span></h3>
<p data-start="366" data-end="670">Deposit and withdrawal fees in crypto exchanges are part of the costs charged for transferring funds and processing transactions. The fees vary depending on the type of asset (crypto or fiat), the method of transfer, network congestion for crypto withdrawals, and the exchange’s specific fee structure.</p>
<p data-start="672" data-end="873">Sometimes, deposits are free, while withdrawals are usually charged with a fee that can be either a fixed amount or a percentage, and there might be an additional network fee for crypto transactions.</p>
<p data-start="875" data-end="1067">Let’s say you’re depositing $1,000 via debit card. In that case, you might face a 2.5% deposit fee, which translates to $25 disappearing instantly. This means your balance will reflect $975.</p>
<p data-start="1069" data-end="1369">When it comes to deposit fees, the method you choose really makes a difference. Bank transfers are typically the most affordable option, sometimes even free, but they can take their sweet time. On the other hand, card payments are quicker, though they do come with their own set of processing fees.</p>
<p data-start="1371" data-end="1647">Each payment method carries its own risks and costs for the exchange. For instance, card payments can be disputed, bank wires might get delayed, and third-party processors often take a slice of the pie. In most cases, service providers will pass those costs right on to you.</p>
<h3><strong>Additional Fees</strong></h3>
<p><b>Spreads</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: A spread refers to the gap between the buying and selling prices.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Every time you trade at market price, you end up paying that difference. Even if an exchange advertises low trading fees, if the spreads are wide, you’re essentially losing money.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Some innovative trading platforms might promote zero-fee trades, but they often compensate by widening the spread to make their profits. Others might narrow the spread but charge higher trading fees. Either way, it’s still a cost you need to consider.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">For instance, if you’re trading $1000 worth of crypto and the spread is 1%, that means you’re losing $10 just due to the pricing difference.</span></p>
<p><b>Inactivity Fees</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: Certain crypto trading platforms will hit you with fees if your account sits idle for too long. If you haven’t logged in or made a trade in several months, they might start charging you a monthly fee.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">These fees are usually pretty small, around $2 to $5 a month, but they can add up over time. You might not even realize it until you log back in and notice your balance is lower.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Inactivity fees are meant to cover things like account maintenance, data storage, and compliance checks. At least, that’s how exchanges explain them. From a user’s point of view, they just feel like another cost for doing nothing.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Always take a moment to check the terms of service to see if these fees apply to you. They’re often hidden in the fine print.</span></p>
<h2><strong>How to Reduce Your Exchange Fees?</strong></h2>
<h3><strong>Signing up with a referral code</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Signing up with a referral code is a smart move! Most crypto exchanges have referral programs that reward both the person who refers and the new user with lower trading fees. When you sign up using a referral code, you can often snag an instant discount, sometimes as much as 20%, on trading fees. It’s a simple way to start saving right from the get-go, without having to hit any specific trading volume targets.</span></p>
<h3><strong>Loyalty/VIP programs</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Loyalty/VIP programs are another great way to save. Many exchanges have tiered loyalty or VIP systems that depend on your trading volume over the last 30 days or your account balance. As you climb the tiers, your trading fees decrease. Plus, reaching higher levels can unlock some sweet perks like quicker withdrawals or priority support. Keeping an eye on your progress toward the next tier can help you plan your trades smartly to qualify for those lower fees.</span></p>
<h3><strong>Using native tokens</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Some exchanges have their own tokens (like BNB on Binance or OKB on OKX). If you pay your fees with their coin, you get a discount—usually 10–25%. Saves you cash and, honestly, helps pump their own token’s value. </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">This is a win-win: users pay less, and the exchange gets to boost the utility of their tokens.</span></p>
<h3><strong>Staking discounts</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A few exchanges let you stake certain cryptocurrencies or native tokens in exchange for lower trading fees. While staking does lock up your funds for a while, the fee reductions (and sometimes extra staking rewards) can make it a worthwhile option for active traders. Be sure to check out each exchange’s staking tiers to see what kind of discount you can earn.</span></p>
<h3><strong>Trading during low-volume hours</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lastly, trading during low-volume hours can be a game changer. Even though trading fees are generally fixed, the actual cost can spike during high volatility due to slippage and wider spreads. By executing trades during low-volume or off-peak hours when there’s still enough liquidity but less volatility, you can help keep those hidden costs down, making your trading experience more efficient.</span></p>
<h2 data-pm-slice="1 1 []"><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Final Thoughts: Choosing the Right Cryptocurrency Exchange With Lowest Fees</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In 2026, crypto traders have more options than ever, but fees still play a crucial role in determining profitability. Exchanges like MEXC and Pionex are at the forefront with their ultra-low or even zero maker fees. Meanwhile, big names like Binance, OKX, and KuCoin strike a balance between affordability and offering deep liquidity, advanced tools, and token-based discounts.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">For those who value convenience and a smooth user experience, platforms like Crypto.com and Coinbase are still attractive, even if they come with higher base rates. On the other hand, Bitget, Bybit, and BingX are drawing in traders with features like copy trading, derivatives, and social tools that provide added value beyond just saving on fees.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In the end, the ideal low-fee exchange really depends on your trading style, location, and volume. High-frequency traders can reap the most benefits from maker rebates and token discounts, while casual users might prioritize simplicity and reliability. By getting a good grasp of each exchange’s fee structure, from maker/taker pricing to token-based savings, you can select the crypto exchange with lowest fees that helps you keep costs down and boosts your long-term returns.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">FAQs</span></h2>
<h3><strong>Which crypto exchange has the lowest withdrawal fees?</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Among the exchanges discussed, </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/mexc-review/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400;">MEXC</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> has relatively low withdrawal fees. However, MEXC states that withdrawal fees vary by cryptocurrency. </span></p>
<h3><strong>Which crypto exchange has the lowest futures fees?</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">MEXC has the lowest futures fees</span></p>
<h3><strong>Which crypto exchange has the lowest spot trading fees?</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">MEXC has the lowest spot trading fees</span></p>
<h3><strong>Which crypto exchange has the lowest credit card fees?</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Kraken is frequently mentioned in crypto-fee guides as one of the exchanges with competitive credit card fees, which start from 0% up to 0.26%. In contrast, other well-known exchanges such as Binance and Coinbase often charge fees that fall between 1% and 4% or even higher for credit card transactions.</span></p>
<h3><strong>Which crypto exchange has the lowest deposit fees?</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Deposit fees for several exchanges, including MEXC, are very little or nonexistent.</span></p>
<h3><strong>Which crypto exchange has the lowest transfer fees?</strong></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There’s no exchange that can honestly say it has the “lowest transfer fee” all the time — it varies based on the blockchain, how busy it is, and other factors.</span></p>
<h3 data-pm-slice="1 1 []"><span data-color="var(--green-10)">How Do Fees on Decentralized Exchanges Compare?</span></h3>
<p><span data-color="var(--green-10)">ecentralized exchanges typically charge a swap fee plus </span><strong><span data-color="var(--green-10)">blockchain gas fees</span></strong><span data-color="var(--green-10)">. This often makes them more expensive than centralized platforms like MEXC, especially during high network congestion.</span></p>
<h3><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Which Exchange Has the Best Customer Service?</span></h3>
<p><span data-color="var(--green-10)">While low-fee options like MEXC prioritize cost savings, platforms like Kraken and Coinbase are widely considered to have the </span><strong><span data-color="var(--green-10)">best customer service</span></strong><span data-color="var(--green-10)"> due to their responsive support teams.</span></p>
