					<description><![CDATA[<p>Dream Raises $260M to Accelerate Sovereign AI Expansion Dream raised $260 million in a Series D round led by Bicycle Capital and Group 11, with participation from Antler, Bain Capital</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/dream-raises-260m-sovereign-ai-expansion/" data-wpel-link="internal">Dream Raises $260M to Expand Sovereign AI and Cyber Defence Platforms</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Dream Raises $260M to Accelerate Sovereign AI Expansion</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Dream raised $260 million in a Series D round led by Bicycle Capital and Group 11, with participation from Antler, Bain Capital Ventures, Tru Arrow Partners, and other investors. It develops sovereign AI and cyber defence solutions for governments and critical infrastructure operators. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This investment brings the company’s valuation to $3 billion at the time it has just launched its commercial activity in late 2024, three years after its founding. The company achieved nearly $300 million in contract value over the past 12 months. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company has generated more than $130 million in annual </span><a href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/r/recurringrevenue.asp" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">recurring revenue</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> from government clients across Europe, Asia-Pacific, and the Middle East. It plans to use the funding to accelerate adoption of its cyber defence and AI platforms across Europe, the Americas, Asia, and the Middle East.</span></p>
<h2><b>Governments Seek Greater Control Over Critical AI Systems</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Intelligence and artificial intelligence (AI) are now being considered national strategic resources and while countries need AI for government services, national security, and economic growth, they still mostly rely on technology developed and owned by non-national tech giants. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Dream says foreign-controlled technology threatens national sovereignty, resilience, and independence. The company was founded to offer a different solution by providing tools for the public sector to control their AI operations. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Their products can assist the government in safeguarding critical data and delivering powerful AI functionality in an independent infrastructure. Dream maintains that the solution also increases independence from providers and helps with national resilience. Shalev Hulio, Dream </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Each nation must be empowered to secure its national data and deploy intelligent solutions independently.” Sebastian Kurz, Dream co-founder and former Chancellor of Austria, said in the announcement, “ Sovereign AI will provide the groundwork for a secure and resilient country.”</span></p>
<h2><b>Three Platforms Power Dream’s National Security Strategy</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_202946" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202946" class="size-full wp-image-202946" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Dream-2.png" alt="A sovereign national security AI system showing three integrated platforms—cyber defense, autonomous vulnerability detection, and sovereign data intelligence—protecting critical infrastructure." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-202946" class="wp-caption-text">Dream’s national security strategy is powered by three integrated AI platforms—Sphere, Hero, and Atlas—delivering unified cyber defense, autonomous threat detection, and sovereign data intelligence for governments securing critical infrastructure. Source: Created by Ventureburn</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Dream has developed three core platforms designed specifically for government customers. Together, they help organisations secure information, identify threats, and extract value from national datasets.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The first platform, Sphere, functions as a national cyber defence system. It combines cyber intelligence, exposure management, attack path analysis, digital twin technology, and AI-powered threat detection. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The platform provides governments with a unified view of risks across critical infrastructure networks, helping identify threats before they escalate. Hero serves as an autonomous AI security researcher.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The system continuously searches for vulnerabilities, analyses attack paths, and simulates adversarial behaviour at machine speed. This enables governments to strengthen digital defences before attacks occur.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Atlas completes the platform suite as Dream’s sovereign AI solution. It connects fragmented data sources, transforms information into structured knowledge, and supports mission-specific AI agents. Governments can generate actionable insights while maintaining full control of their data within secure environments.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/flutterwave-raises-250m-series-e/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Flutterwave Raises $250M Series E at $3.2B Valuation with Ripple Strategic Backing</span></a></p>
<h2><b>Rising Cyber Threats Fuel Investor Interest</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">With a greater emphasis on nation-state directed cyber-attacks, advanced defense technologies have seen a rise in demand, especially on the backdrop of state backed attacks targeting critically important assets such as energy, healthcare networks, transit and communication networks. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">It appears to many governments that previously commercial focused security products developed for enterprises do not fit the requirements for state run infrastructure.Dream plans to bridge this space by offering comprehensive security monitoring, an AI-driven threat assessment and sovereign wide scale cyber-resilience. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Investors are certainly sold on the prospect: Dream has seen its valuation grow from around $1.1 billion in early 2025 to a present valuation of$3 billion, fuelled by the companies ability to acquire state contractand command a high price tag.The story is emblematic of larger shifts underway in the tech landscape. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Governments now view AI infrastructure as on par with infrastructure of national security, like power lines and telecommunication networks. The ongoing push by sovereign governments to develop their own domestic technology capability has seenDream position itself in a crucial part of this development.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To stay updated on crypto venture capital funding and market trends, visit our </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/category/news/venture-capital/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">venture capital news section</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> for more insights.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/dream-raises-260m-sovereign-ai-expansion/" data-wpel-link="internal">Dream Raises $260M to Expand Sovereign AI and Cyber Defence Platforms</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
